02:45.000 --> 02:48.000
So, once again, look.

02:48.000 --> 02:52.000
Our first topic is introduction to economics.

02:52.000 --> 02:54.000
Two questions on this topic.

02:54.000 --> 02:58.000
The first question is economics as a science.

02:58.000 --> 03:03.000
Well, the topic is introductory, I will dwell on it very briefly.

03:03.000 --> 03:07.000
And first of all, I would like to tell you

03:07.000 --> 03:10.000
what kind of science is economics.

03:10.000 --> 03:13.000
Where did it come from? How did it arise?

03:13.000 --> 03:18.000
It arose from a very simple contradiction.

03:18.000 --> 03:22.000
People's needs are limitless,

03:22.000 --> 03:27.000
and the resources they have to meet these needs,

03:27.000 --> 03:30.000
unfortunately, are limited.

03:30.000 --> 03:37.000
And if soon it is so, then there is a problem of choice.

03:37.000 --> 03:42.000
Well, a couple of elementary examples.

03:42.000 --> 03:44.000
Let's say you come to a store.

03:44.000 --> 03:46.000
No matter how rich you are,

03:46.000 --> 03:50.000
the amount of money you have is limited.

03:50.000 --> 03:55.000
But you will not buy only bread or only milk.

03:55.000 --> 03:57.000
What is your task?

03:57.000 --> 04:03.000
You need to buy an optimal set of goods

04:03.000 --> 04:08.000
for the limited amount of money you have.

04:08.000 --> 04:14.000
That is, the set that best satisfies your needs.

04:14.000 --> 04:18.000
That is, you solve a typical economic problem

04:18.000 --> 04:20.000
related to the problem of choice.

04:20.000 --> 04:22.000
Or a company.

04:22.000 --> 04:24.000
The company cannot produce everything.

04:24.000 --> 04:27.000
It also has limited resources.

04:27.000 --> 04:29.000
What is its task?

04:29.000 --> 04:33.000
The best way to use the limited resources

04:33.000 --> 04:36.000
to get the maximum profit.

04:36.000 --> 04:40.000
Local authorities would like to build a school,

04:40.000 --> 04:42.000
a road and a hospital.

04:42.000 --> 04:45.000
But again, there is not enough resources for everything.

04:45.000 --> 04:48.000
Again, you have to choose.

04:48.000 --> 05:04.000
So, this is what economic theory does.

05:04.000 --> 05:08.000
And now, please look at the next slide.

05:08.000 --> 05:11.000
The subject of economics.

05:11.000 --> 05:14.000
That is, what does economics study?

05:14.000 --> 05:15.000
Here we look.

05:15.000 --> 05:19.000
The subject of economics is the decisions made in society

05:19.000 --> 05:22.000
when distributing limited resources

05:22.000 --> 05:25.000
between different options of their use

05:25.000 --> 05:29.000
in order to maximize the well-being of people.

05:29.000 --> 05:32.000
But this is what I have already told you about.

05:32.000 --> 05:37.000
Economic theory is about how people, companies, society as a whole

05:37.000 --> 05:41.000
make their choice in conditions of limited resources.

05:43.000 --> 05:45.000
Let's look further.

05:45.000 --> 05:47.000
The next slide.

05:48.000 --> 05:52.000
If you have to make a choice soon,

05:52.000 --> 05:55.000
you should answer three basic questions.

05:56.000 --> 05:59.000
The first question is what and how much to produce.

05:59.000 --> 06:02.000
The second question is how to produce.

06:02.000 --> 06:05.000
The third question is for whom to produce.

06:05.000 --> 06:08.000
Again, the simplest example.

06:10.000 --> 06:15.000
Local authorities would like to build a school, a road and a hospital.

06:15.000 --> 06:18.000
But again, there is not enough resources for everything.

06:18.000 --> 06:23.000
The first question they have to answer is what to produce.

06:23.000 --> 06:25.000
Okay.

06:25.000 --> 06:28.000
Let's say they chose the road.

06:29.000 --> 06:32.000
But another question comes up.

06:32.000 --> 06:36.000
In fact, the road can be built in different ways.

06:36.000 --> 06:41.000
You can hire a regiment of soldiers with shovels,

06:41.000 --> 06:46.000
or you can use less manual labor and more machines.

06:46.000 --> 06:48.000
What is the point?

06:48.000 --> 06:52.000
The choice of the best production technology.

06:52.000 --> 06:56.000
That is, you have to answer the question how to produce.

06:56.000 --> 06:58.000
Okay.

06:58.000 --> 07:01.000
Let's say we built a road.

07:01.000 --> 07:04.000
The pie is baked.

07:04.000 --> 07:07.000
What should we do next?

07:07.000 --> 07:10.000
We have to divide the pie.

07:10.000 --> 07:15.000
So the question is for whom to produce.

07:15.000 --> 07:20.000
In the application of the road, you can do this.

07:20.000 --> 07:24.000
You can make the road paid or free.

07:25.000 --> 07:30.000
If we make the road free,

07:30.000 --> 07:35.000
we answered the question for whom to produce, for whom the road.

07:35.000 --> 07:40.000
If the road is free, then the road is for everyone.

07:40.000 --> 07:47.000
If it is paid, then it is already a road for those who can pay the required amount.

07:47.000 --> 07:49.000
A compromise option is possible.

07:49.000 --> 07:54.000
The road can be free for the residents of our region and paid for the residents of other regions.

07:54.000 --> 08:01.000
So, these are the three main questions of the economic choice.

08:01.000 --> 08:06.000
And then, look.

08:06.000 --> 08:12.000
I have already said that the economic theory consists of two parts.

08:12.000 --> 08:16.000
Microeconomics and macroeconomics.

08:16.000 --> 08:19.000
What do they study?

08:19.000 --> 08:21.000
Look at the slide.

08:21.000 --> 08:28.000
Microeconomics studies the behavior of individual economic agents

08:28.000 --> 08:33.000
and their interaction in individual markets.

08:33.000 --> 08:42.000
Individual economic agents can be, for example, a separate company or a separate household.

08:43.000 --> 08:49.000
And in the center of microeconomics attention are the prices and volumes of production of individual goods,

08:49.000 --> 08:55.000
the choice of an individual consumer, the release of resources of an individual company, and so on.

08:57.000 --> 09:05.000
Macroeconomics, in turn, studies the people's economy as a whole, as a single system.

09:05.000 --> 09:11.000
And in the center of its attention are the general indicators of public production,

09:11.000 --> 09:18.000
such as GDP, economic growth, unemployment, inflation, and so on.

09:20.000 --> 09:24.000
Let's look at a few simple examples.

09:26.000 --> 09:32.000
Let's say that the company X fired 100 people.

09:33.000 --> 09:37.000
What sphere does this relate to?

09:37.000 --> 09:41.000
Obviously, to the microeconomics. Why?

09:41.000 --> 09:48.000
Because it is about the behavior of a separate enterprise.

09:51.000 --> 09:55.000
In Russia, the level of unemployment has decreased.

09:55.000 --> 10:00.000
In this case, it is about the economy as a whole.

10:00.000 --> 10:04.000
And this issue is related to the macroeconomics.

10:06.000 --> 10:17.000
But if the world oil prices have sharply increased due to the war in the Middle East?

10:19.000 --> 10:20.000
Think about it.

10:21.000 --> 10:22.000
Micro or macro?

10:25.000 --> 10:26.000
In fact, micro.

10:27.000 --> 10:28.000
In fact, microeconomics.

10:28.000 --> 10:29.000
Why?

10:30.000 --> 10:39.000
Because in this case, we are talking about the market of a separate commodity, even a very large market.

10:41.000 --> 10:47.000
The microeconomics studies the markets of separate commodities.

10:48.000 --> 10:54.000
But a separate market is not necessarily a market in our village.

10:55.000 --> 10:59.000
A separate market can be the world market.

10:59.000 --> 11:01.000
For example, the world oil market.

11:03.000 --> 11:05.000
This is a subject of microeconomics.

11:08.000 --> 11:12.000
And a couple of comments on the same subject.

11:13.000 --> 11:22.000
It should not be thought that the microeconomics is engaged in some less important, less significant things.

11:23.000 --> 11:26.000
In fact, everything big is made up of small.

11:27.000 --> 11:34.000
It is impossible to understand how the forest develops if we do not know the laws by which individual trees grow.

11:35.000 --> 11:40.000
And in general, look, the prefix micro literally means small.

11:41.000 --> 11:43.000
But the matter is not in size at all.

11:45.000 --> 11:51.000
The object of microeconomics may be larger than the object of macroeconomics.

11:52.000 --> 11:53.000
The simplest example.

11:54.000 --> 11:55.000
For example, Microsoft.

11:56.000 --> 11:57.000
A separate company.

11:58.000 --> 12:03.000
Its activity is related to the course of microeconomics.

12:04.000 --> 12:13.000
But at the same time, in terms of the volume of the annual release, Microsoft exceeds the head of the internal product, for example, of Luxembourg.

12:14.000 --> 12:18.000
But the economy of Luxembourg is macroeconomics.

12:18.000 --> 12:19.000
The object of macroeconomics.

12:19.000 --> 12:20.000
What happens?

12:21.000 --> 12:26.000
The object of microeconomics, I repeat, may be larger than the object of macroeconomics.

12:27.000 --> 12:29.000
Another comment.

12:30.000 --> 12:36.000
It is not necessary to divide micro and macroeconomics with a single wall.

12:37.000 --> 12:40.000
In fact, they smoothly flow from one to another.

12:43.000 --> 12:47.000
And then look at the next slide.

12:48.000 --> 12:52.000
We will talk about very important things.

12:53.000 --> 12:56.000
About economic costs.

12:57.000 --> 13:05.000
I have already said that the main problem of economic theory is the problem of rational choice.

13:06.000 --> 13:12.000
And if we make a choice soon, the concept of economic costs arises.

13:13.000 --> 13:18.000
This is probably the most important concept in the course of economics.

13:19.000 --> 13:21.000
Therefore, I will dwell on it in more detail.

13:22.000 --> 13:24.000
First, the definition.

13:25.000 --> 13:29.000
At first glance, it may seem difficult to you.

13:30.000 --> 13:32.000
In fact, there is nothing difficult.

13:33.000 --> 13:34.000
I will explain.

13:35.000 --> 13:36.000
Look at the definition.

13:37.000 --> 13:38.000
We read.

13:38.000 --> 13:55.000
Economic costs of obtaining a certain benefit are other benefits that could be obtained with the same resources,

13:56.000 --> 14:04.000
but from which you will have to refuse if the choice is made in favor of this benefit.

14:05.000 --> 14:14.000
I strongly suspect that, firstly, nothing is clear, some three-stage definition.

14:15.000 --> 14:17.000
In fact, let's figure it out.

14:18.000 --> 14:20.000
Let's use your example.

14:21.000 --> 14:26.000
You came to study some science.

14:27.000 --> 14:29.000
Let's say, the same economy.

14:30.000 --> 14:39.000
Tell me, please, answer yourself the question, what are your costs of studying this course?

14:40.000 --> 14:42.000
In fact, we are talking about costs.

14:43.000 --> 14:44.000
Let me explain.

14:45.000 --> 14:48.000
What are your costs of studying economics?

14:49.000 --> 14:58.000
Well, it is quite likely that many of you, first of all, remembered the tuition fee.

15:00.000 --> 15:05.000
In fact, it does not matter how much you pay, but how much you pay.

15:06.000 --> 15:10.000
Of course, the tuition fee is your expenses.

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
But economists make a certain adjustment.

15:16.000 --> 15:31.000
Look, now the annual course of study at the Moscow University of Economics costs about 7,000 units.

15:32.000 --> 15:41.000
But at the end of the 19th century, the same annual course cost about 30 rubles.

15:41.000 --> 15:47.000
Does it mean that the tuition fee was cheap at that time, and now it has become expensive?

15:48.000 --> 15:50.000
I hope you understand that it is not the case.

15:51.000 --> 15:53.000
So, what do economists say?

15:54.000 --> 16:02.000
Economists say that when you pay money for some benefit, for example, education,

16:03.000 --> 16:17.000
you spend, you lose not the money itself, but some other benefits that you could have acquired for this money.

16:18.000 --> 16:30.000
These unobtained benefits and your losses or your expenses associated with the obtained, considered benefit.

16:31.000 --> 16:44.000
For example, you could study economics, and you could spend this money on vacation.

16:45.000 --> 16:46.000
So, what happens?

16:47.000 --> 16:54.000
If you study economics, you will not be able to relax normally.

16:55.000 --> 16:58.000
These are your losses associated with studying economics.

16:58.000 --> 17:03.000
Someone, instead of studying economics, could buy a new fur coat.

17:04.000 --> 17:12.000
So, the expenses associated with studying this course, the absence of a fur coat, are losses or expenses.

17:13.000 --> 17:14.000
Well, okay.

17:15.000 --> 17:19.000
What else do you lose by studying economics?

17:20.000 --> 17:26.000
In addition to paying for your studies, you also lose time.

17:26.000 --> 17:38.000
But again, not the time itself, but some benefits that you could have acquired, received during this time.

17:39.000 --> 17:41.000
What benefits do you lose?

17:42.000 --> 17:43.000
Each in a different way.

17:44.000 --> 17:52.000
Someone, instead of studying, could work more, earn more money.

17:52.000 --> 17:57.000
So, what goes into the economic costs of education?

17:58.000 --> 18:05.000
The lost salary, or rather the benefits that could have been acquired for this salary.

18:06.000 --> 18:10.000
Someone, instead of studying, could repair an apartment.

18:11.000 --> 18:13.000
According to the alternative costs, what goes into it?

18:14.000 --> 18:19.000
The dissatisfaction of living in an unrepaired, dirty apartment.

18:19.000 --> 18:26.000
Someone, instead of studying, could raise a child.

18:27.000 --> 18:29.000
So, what goes into the alternative costs of education?

18:30.000 --> 18:31.000
An uneducated child.

18:32.000 --> 18:35.000
Someone could just relax.

18:36.000 --> 18:39.000
So, what goes into the alternative costs of education?

18:40.000 --> 18:44.000
The lost pleasure of watching your favorite TV series.

18:45.000 --> 18:47.000
So, what happens?

18:48.000 --> 18:55.000
In order to assess the alternative costs of obtaining this benefit...

18:56.000 --> 19:00.000
I forgot to say, alternative costs and economic costs are synonyms.

19:01.000 --> 19:06.000
In order to assess the alternative costs of obtaining this benefit,

19:07.000 --> 19:15.000
you need to assess all the losses that you incur in this regard.

19:16.000 --> 19:19.000
And then, in order to bring these losses to a common denominator,

19:20.000 --> 19:26.000
the value of these losses, of course, would be desirable to be expressed in monetary units.

19:27.000 --> 19:32.000
Well, I would like to make a couple of comments on alternative costs.

19:33.000 --> 19:35.000
Very important, which must be taken into account.

19:36.000 --> 19:37.000
The first comment.

19:38.000 --> 19:45.000
Alternative costs arise only where there is an alternative.

19:46.000 --> 19:53.000
There is no alternative, there are no alternative or economic costs.

19:53.000 --> 19:55.000
Let's take an example.

19:56.000 --> 20:03.000
I have already said that we are considering a situation when you decide to study some new course.

20:04.000 --> 20:11.000
During the course, you have to spend money on food.

20:12.000 --> 20:22.000
Will the food expenses go into the alternative costs of obtaining education?

20:23.000 --> 20:25.000
No, they will not.

20:26.000 --> 20:27.000
And here is why.

20:28.000 --> 20:35.000
Because you have to eat in any case, regardless of whether you are studying or not.

20:36.000 --> 20:37.000
I repeat again.

20:38.000 --> 20:47.000
Alternative costs arise only where there is an alternative.

20:48.000 --> 20:56.000
If you have to bear expenses, regardless of whether you are studying or not,

20:57.000 --> 21:02.000
then economists do not include these expenses in alternative costs.

21:04.000 --> 21:08.000
Let's take an example.

21:09.000 --> 21:10.000
Here is a road.

21:10.000 --> 21:21.000
It leads from point A to point B.

21:22.000 --> 21:26.000
As it turns out, there are two lanes.

21:27.000 --> 21:33.000
On this side, cars go from A to B.

21:34.000 --> 21:39.000
On this side, cars obviously go from B to A.

21:40.000 --> 21:44.000
You have to get to the car from A to B.

21:45.000 --> 21:47.000
Where will you catch the car?

21:48.000 --> 21:50.000
Which side will you stand on?

21:51.000 --> 21:58.000
Obviously, elementary experience tells you that you will stand somewhere here.

21:59.000 --> 22:07.000
Explain your behavior from the point of view of the theory of alternative costs.

22:08.000 --> 22:13.000
I will say right away that the time to turn from A to B,

22:14.000 --> 22:17.000
if the car goes like this, and you decided to stand here,

22:18.000 --> 22:20.000
we will consider the time to turn to be equal to zero.

22:21.000 --> 22:23.000
Why are you standing here?

22:24.000 --> 22:26.000
Let's discuss.

22:27.000 --> 22:29.000
What do you want?

22:30.000 --> 22:37.000
Obviously, you want to get from A to B as cheaply as possible.

22:38.000 --> 22:45.000
And obviously, you think that the driver will take with you the smaller the amount,

22:46.000 --> 22:48.000
the less his expenses.

22:49.000 --> 22:51.000
So, there is a question.

22:52.000 --> 22:57.000
What are the alternative costs of a driver for transportation?

22:57.000 --> 23:05.000
For transportation, you, from A to B, if he still goes there,

23:06.000 --> 23:12.000
they are equal to zero or close to zero.

23:13.000 --> 23:14.000
Why?

23:15.000 --> 23:18.000
Because if he still goes in this direction,

23:19.000 --> 23:28.000
then neither his time, nor the fuel consumption will be included in the alternative costs for transportation.

23:29.000 --> 23:31.000
He still goes in this direction.

23:32.000 --> 23:35.000
Of course, he will have alternative costs.

23:36.000 --> 23:38.000
But what are they related to?

23:39.000 --> 23:43.000
To the reluctance to have a stranger in the cabin.

23:44.000 --> 23:46.000
Who knows what you will throw there.

23:46.000 --> 23:48.000
But if you are a pretty lady,

23:49.000 --> 23:52.000
I dare to assure you that there are no costs here,

23:53.000 --> 23:55.000
only benefits.

23:56.000 --> 24:03.000
Therefore, a lady's car will probably cost faster than a man's.

24:04.000 --> 24:11.000
And look, what would happen if you caught a car standing here?

24:12.000 --> 24:14.000
Cars go from B to A.

24:14.000 --> 24:16.000
And you need from A to B.

24:17.000 --> 24:19.000
You will turn the car around.

24:20.000 --> 24:26.000
But then the alternative costs of the driver will be much higher.

24:27.000 --> 24:33.000
Then, in the alternative costs of the driver for transportation from A to B,

24:34.000 --> 24:36.000
if he goes from B to A,

24:37.000 --> 24:39.000
all these expenses will be included,

24:40.000 --> 24:42.000
and the lost time,

24:42.000 --> 24:44.000
and the lost time,

24:45.000 --> 24:47.000
and the costs of fuel and everything else.

24:48.000 --> 24:52.000
Imagine that here in point A is an international airport,

24:53.000 --> 24:57.000
and the driver is going to fly away to rest abroad.

24:58.000 --> 25:00.000
You will turn him around.

25:01.000 --> 25:04.000
He will not go to the airport, but he will take you to B.

25:05.000 --> 25:07.000
But you will have to pay him a lot.

25:07.000 --> 25:13.000
Because his alternative costs in this case will be very high.

25:14.000 --> 25:18.000
We live in an alternative world.

25:19.000 --> 25:22.000
There are a lot of alternatives.

25:23.000 --> 25:28.000
So, all alternatives at the same time are impossible to implement.

25:29.000 --> 25:37.000
Therefore, when you evaluate alternative costs of getting some benefit,

25:38.000 --> 25:44.000
you need to choose the best alternative.

25:45.000 --> 25:47.000
For example,

25:48.000 --> 25:50.000
let's say,

25:51.000 --> 25:56.000
a certain lady has a choice today.

25:57.000 --> 26:03.000
She has several alternatives for tonight.

26:04.000 --> 26:09.000
Well, what alternatives can there be for tonight?

26:10.000 --> 26:12.000
To rest.

26:13.000 --> 26:15.000
To rest.

26:16.000 --> 26:18.000
To rest, just stay at home and watch TV.

26:19.000 --> 26:22.000
To meet, for example, with FOMO.

