47:33.000 --> 47:37.000
But wait, I forgot one point.

47:38.000 --> 47:41.000
Look again at all the demand factors.

47:42.000 --> 47:43.000
How many are there?

47:43.000 --> 47:46.000
I have 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8.

47:47.000 --> 47:48.000
Eight demand factors.

47:49.000 --> 47:51.000
And what do you think, what do you think?

47:52.000 --> 47:54.000
What is the important factor,

47:55.000 --> 47:58.000
very important, obviously, in terms of life,

47:59.000 --> 48:00.000
which affects the demand?

48:01.000 --> 48:02.000
I did not mention.

48:03.000 --> 48:04.000
What factor is not mentioned?

48:05.000 --> 48:07.000
Obviously, I did not say anything about the quality of the product.

48:08.000 --> 48:09.000
But do not hurry.

48:09.000 --> 48:12.000
Do not include quality in the number of demand factors.

48:13.000 --> 48:15.000
That's why economists do not do this.

48:16.000 --> 48:21.000
Because we are talking about the demand for a given product.

48:22.000 --> 48:30.000
And the demand for a given product implies the demand for a product of a given quality.

48:31.000 --> 48:34.000
That is, we initially consider the quality of the product to be set.

48:34.000 --> 48:37.000
If the quality changes,

48:38.000 --> 48:41.000
then we consider it as another product,

48:42.000 --> 48:43.000
although a very close substitute.

48:44.000 --> 48:48.000
In other words, the Zhiguli 10 and 12 models

48:49.000 --> 48:51.000
are considered as different benefits in the microeconomy.

48:52.000 --> 48:55.000
Moreover, even Zhiguli of different colors

48:56.000 --> 48:58.000
are also considered as different benefits in the microeconomy.

48:59.000 --> 49:00.000
Is it clear?

49:00.000 --> 49:04.000
We consider the quality of the product to be initially set.

49:05.000 --> 49:08.000
Therefore, it is not mentioned in the number of demand factors.

49:09.000 --> 49:14.000
Now let's talk more specifically about the demand factors.

49:15.000 --> 49:21.000
The first factor, I repeat, is the price of a given product.

49:22.000 --> 49:28.000
Let's see how the price of a given product affects the demand for it.

49:30.000 --> 49:31.000
It's very easy.

49:32.000 --> 49:37.000
There is a so-called law of demand in the microeconomy.

49:38.000 --> 49:39.000
Let's look at the next slide.

49:40.000 --> 49:41.000
Here is its formulation.

49:42.000 --> 49:44.000
The law of demand.

49:45.000 --> 49:48.000
The lower the price of a given product,

49:49.000 --> 49:55.000
the more customers want to purchase it

49:56.000 --> 49:58.000
during a given period of time

49:58.000 --> 50:02.000
and under other unchanged conditions.

50:03.000 --> 50:08.000
The law of demand is reflected graphically.

50:09.000 --> 50:11.000
Look at the graph.

50:12.000 --> 50:17.000
Look, we put the quantity of the product along the x-axis.

50:18.000 --> 50:20.000
I use the internationally accepted designation

50:21.000 --> 50:22.000
of quantity.

50:23.000 --> 50:24.000
It means Q.

50:24.000 --> 50:30.000
And along the y-axis we put the price of a given product.

50:31.000 --> 50:32.000
And what do we see?

50:33.000 --> 50:34.000
Look carefully at the graph.

50:35.000 --> 50:36.000
I think it's not difficult.

50:37.000 --> 50:41.000
The lower the price of a product,

50:42.000 --> 50:47.000
the more demand for it

50:48.000 --> 50:52.000
under other unchanged conditions.

50:53.000 --> 50:55.000
Just a small caveat.

50:56.000 --> 50:59.000
You see, I drew the function of demand as a linear one.

51:01.000 --> 51:03.000
In fact, it doesn't have to be linear.

51:04.000 --> 51:05.000
It can be non-linear,

51:06.000 --> 51:08.000
it can be like this, curved.

51:09.000 --> 51:11.000
But it doesn't cancel the law of demand.

51:12.000 --> 51:16.000
The linear function of demand is most often used for simplification.

51:17.000 --> 51:21.000
We have seen how the price of a given product

51:22.000 --> 51:24.000
is the first factor.

51:25.000 --> 51:28.000
But there are seven other factors besides the price.

51:29.000 --> 51:30.000
Let's talk about them.

51:31.000 --> 51:33.000
Look at the next slide.

51:34.000 --> 51:39.000
It says that the effect of all other factors on demand

51:40.000 --> 51:44.000
is manifested in the shift of the demand curve

51:46.000 --> 51:47.000
from right to left

51:48.000 --> 51:50.000
when the demand increases

51:50.000 --> 51:55.000
and from left to right when it decreases.

51:56.000 --> 51:57.000
Look at the graph.

51:58.000 --> 52:04.000
Let's assume that the demand function is initially set to D0.

52:05.000 --> 52:09.000
Imagine that the income of consumers has increased.

52:10.000 --> 52:12.000
Nothing else has changed.

52:13.000 --> 52:14.000
What does this mean?

52:14.000 --> 52:19.000
It means that at any possible price

52:20.000 --> 52:26.000
people will want to buy this product more than before.

52:27.000 --> 52:29.000
And the demand curve goes where?

52:30.000 --> 52:31.000
To the right.

52:32.000 --> 52:33.000
The opposite situation.

52:35.000 --> 52:39.000
Let's assume that the income of consumers has decreased.

52:40.000 --> 52:42.000
What will we encounter here?

52:42.000 --> 52:46.000
The most important thing is that at any possible price

52:47.000 --> 52:53.000
people will want to buy this product less than before.

52:54.000 --> 52:57.000
And the demand curve shifts to the left and down.

52:58.000 --> 53:00.000
What was the fourth factor?

53:01.000 --> 53:04.000
The fourth factor is the income of consumers.

53:06.000 --> 53:08.000
What is the fifth factor?

53:08.000 --> 53:12.000
The fifth factor is the habits and tastes of consumers.

53:13.000 --> 53:14.000
I think it's obvious.

53:15.000 --> 53:17.000
Imagine this situation.

53:18.000 --> 53:26.000
Russian consumers suddenly fell in love with Estonian products.

53:27.000 --> 53:28.000
For example, sour cream.

53:29.000 --> 53:30.000
What will this lead to?

53:32.000 --> 53:35.000
That the demand for sour cream, for Estonian sour cream,

53:35.000 --> 53:41.000
will decrease and the demand curve will shift to the left.

53:42.000 --> 53:45.000
Look, this is what is important to keep in mind.

53:46.000 --> 53:49.000
What I'm telling you now seems very simple conceptually.

53:50.000 --> 53:56.000
But it's very important to learn how to translate words into the language of graphics.

53:57.000 --> 54:01.000
I said that if Russians suddenly discovered

54:01.000 --> 54:04.000
harmful properties of Estonian sour cream,

54:05.000 --> 54:10.000
the demand for sour cream will decrease and the curve will shift to the left.

54:11.000 --> 54:14.000
I really hope that over time Russians will figure it out

54:15.000 --> 54:18.000
and will understand that Estonian sour cream is not so bad.

54:19.000 --> 54:20.000
Moreover, it's very edible.

54:21.000 --> 54:22.000
What will this lead to?

54:23.000 --> 54:27.000
That the demand for sour cream will increase again at the same price.

54:27.000 --> 54:30.000
And the demand curve will shift to the right.

54:31.000 --> 54:36.000
So, we haven't talked about expectations yet.

54:37.000 --> 54:41.000
What expectations are we talking about in the microeconomics?

54:42.000 --> 54:47.000
First of all, expectations of the price of a product.

54:48.000 --> 54:52.000
Imagine that consumers are waiting

54:52.000 --> 54:58.000
for a sought-after product to become more expensive.

54:59.000 --> 55:01.000
What will they do today?

55:02.000 --> 55:06.000
Most likely, they will buy more products today.

55:07.000 --> 55:10.000
There may be a sharp demand for products.

55:11.000 --> 55:16.000
And the demand will increase, and the demand curve will shift to the right.

55:17.000 --> 55:19.000
There are other expectations.

55:19.000 --> 55:22.000
They are waiting for this product to become cheaper.

55:23.000 --> 55:24.000
Why would they buy it today?

55:25.000 --> 55:28.000
Today, the demand for it will decrease under other equal conditions,

55:29.000 --> 55:32.000
and the demand curve will shift to the left.

55:33.000 --> 55:41.000
By the way, some companies often use this in their advertising strategies.

55:42.000 --> 55:48.000
As usual, Don Stroy is trying to lure customers.

55:49.000 --> 55:56.000
They usually say that today the prices are so-so,

55:57.000 --> 56:02.000
but from the first day of the next month, apartments will become more expensive.

56:03.000 --> 56:07.000
What are the company managers trying to do?

56:08.000 --> 56:12.000
They are trying to increase the demand for apartments today.

56:13.000 --> 56:15.000
That is, to shift the demand curve to the right.

56:16.000 --> 56:17.000
Okay.

56:18.000 --> 56:20.000
Let's look at the second factor.

56:21.000 --> 56:22.000
We haven't talked about it yet.

56:23.000 --> 56:24.000
What was the second factor?

56:25.000 --> 56:30.000
If you remember, the second factor was the price and the number of substitutes.

56:31.000 --> 56:44.000
Let's see how the demand for imported cars changes the price of a Zhiguli.

56:45.000 --> 56:52.000
Let's suppose that for one reason or another, imported cars became more expensive.

56:53.000 --> 56:54.000
Look at the slide, please.

56:55.000 --> 57:00.000
The left graph shows the demand for imported cars.

57:01.000 --> 57:11.000
The initial price of cars was P1, and they wanted to buy Q1 imported cars.

57:11.000 --> 57:15.000
Cars became more expensive, and the price became P2.

57:16.000 --> 57:21.000
Accordingly, they want to buy less imported cars.

57:22.000 --> 57:25.000
The demand fell to Q2.

57:26.000 --> 57:29.000
But since imported cars are more expensive,

57:30.000 --> 57:40.000
this means that consumers at any price of Zhiguli want to buy them more than before.

57:41.000 --> 57:47.000
And the demand curve for Zhiguli shifted to the right.

57:48.000 --> 57:56.000
We observed something similar right after the financial crisis of 1998.

57:57.000 --> 57:58.000
Remember what happened there.

57:59.000 --> 58:01.000
The ruble fell sharply.

58:02.000 --> 58:08.000
As a result, the ruble prices for foreign cars increased.

58:08.000 --> 58:12.000
For many consumers, foreign cars became inaccessible.

58:13.000 --> 58:16.000
So they switched to Zhiguli.

58:17.000 --> 58:20.000
And the autobus temporarily solved its problems with the ruble.

58:21.000 --> 58:26.000
The demand for Zhiguli increased, and the demand curve shifted to the right.

58:27.000 --> 58:33.000
Now let's talk about how the markets of additional goods interact with each other.

58:33.000 --> 58:40.000
In relation to cars, additional goods are gasoline.

58:41.000 --> 58:46.000
Let's assume that cars became more expensive.

58:47.000 --> 58:48.000
What would this lead to?

58:49.000 --> 58:57.000
Previously, the price of a car was P1, and they bought Q1 cars.

58:58.000 --> 59:02.000
Now cars cost P2, and they buy Q2 cars.

59:03.000 --> 59:13.000
But by buying fewer cars, we begin to spend less on gasoline,

59:14.000 --> 59:18.000
and the demand curve for gasoline shifts to the left.

59:19.000 --> 59:20.000
The demand for gasoline decreases.

59:21.000 --> 59:26.000
Well, I think I have covered all the factors.

59:26.000 --> 59:27.000
I have looked at them.

59:28.000 --> 59:34.000
And to finish this question, I would like to make a very important remark.

59:35.000 --> 59:36.000
Look at the next slide.

59:37.000 --> 59:43.000
Economists distinguish between the concept of demand and the quantity of demand.

59:44.000 --> 59:50.000
These concepts sound very similar, but they are different concepts.

59:51.000 --> 59:52.000
Let's read.

59:52.000 --> 01:00:01.000
If the change in the purchase of a particular product is influenced by the change in its price,

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:08.000
its own price, then the change in the quantity of demand is mentioned.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:16.000
In this case, the demand curve does not shift, but we follow the demand curve.

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:18.000
Let's go back to the previous slide.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:21.000
Cars, gasoline.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:25.000
What happened to cars?

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:27.000
Cars became more expensive.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:30.000
Now they are bought less.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:34.000
Previously, at the price of P1, they bought Q1 cars.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:39.000
Now, at the price of P2, they buy Q2 cars.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:42.000
Why do they buy fewer cars?

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:44.000
Because they became more expensive.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:51.000
In this case, we say that the quantity of demand on cars has changed.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:57.000
And we follow the demand curve from bottom to top.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:05.000
If the change in the purchase of a particular product is influenced by all other factors,

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:11.000
then the change in the demand itself is mentioned.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:16.000
And here, the demand curve shifts.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:20.000
Let's go back to the previous slide.

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:24.000
Why do they buy less gasoline?

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:27.000
Because cars became more expensive.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:34.000
At the same price of gasoline, they start buying less.

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:42.000
Here, the demand curve shifts to the left, and we say that the demand on gasoline has decreased.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:45.000
Not the quantity of demand, but the demand.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:48.000
That's it. We have finished the first question.

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:50.000
Now let's talk about the second question.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:54.000
The offer and its factors.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:02:01.000
The definition of an offer is as simple as the definition of a demand.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:03.000
Let's read.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:13.000
An offer is the quantity of goods that all manufacturers can and want to produce and sell

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:18.000
during a given time and under certain conditions.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:20.000
The same thing.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:26.000
The demand is how much they want to buy, and the offer is how much they want to produce and sell.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:30.000
Now let's look at the factors of the offer.

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:32.000
There are a lot of them here too.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:37.000
The first factor is the price of the product.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:47.000
The second factor is the profitability of the goods that are competitive to the goods in production.

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:51.000
I'm afraid it's not very clear, but we'll look at it in a specific example.

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:58.000
The third factor is not better, but the profitability of the goods that complement the goods in production.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:01.000
We'll also look at it in an example.

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:04.000
The fourth factor is the costs of the manufacturers.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:08.000
The fifth factor is the state taxes and subsidies.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:10.000
The sixth factor is the number of manufacturers.

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:12.000
The seventh factor is the goal.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:14.000
The eighth factor is the natural conditions.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:16.000
The ninth factor is the expectations of the manufacturers.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:18.000
Let's go on.

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:21.000
We've discussed the factors of demand before.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:24.000
Now let's talk about the factors of the offer.

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:29.000
The first factor of the offer is the price of the product.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:37.000
Here we have what economists call the law of the offer.

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:41.000
Here it is on the next slide.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:44.000
The law of the offer.

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:47.000
The higher the price of a given product,

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:54.000
the more manufacturers want to sell it

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:59.000
during this time and under other unchangeable conditions.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:05.000
You see, this law is opposed to the law of demand.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:07.000
What did the law of demand sound like?

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:12.000
The lower the price, the more they want to buy.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:14.000
What does the law of the offer sound like?

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:22.000
The higher the price, the more they want to sell.

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:23.000
What does the law of demand sound like?

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:25.000
The higher the price, the more they want to sell.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:27.000
Graphically, we have this law.

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:33.000
Again, on the x-axis, we put the quantity of the product.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:36.000
But now it is not the quantity of demand, but the quantity of the offer.

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:40.000
And on the y-axis, again, the price of the product.

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:42.000
And what do we see?

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:44.000
The ascending function.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:49.000
The higher the price of the product,

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:58.000
the more manufacturers want to produce and sell it.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:00.000
Why is that?

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:08.000
Let's look at it with a simple conditional example.

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:13.000
Let's look at a completely conditional example.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:22.000
Let's assume that there are only three oil fields in the world.

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:28.000
On each field, according to the natural conditions,

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:33.000
you can extract only one conditional barrel of oil.

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:35.000
No more.

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:37.000
We introduce it for the sake of simplicity.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:40.000
Such a simplification.

01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:43.000
But what is obvious?

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:49.000
Every manufacturer would like to sell their oil as expensive as possible.

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:51.000
Even for a million dollars.

01:05:52.000 --> 01:06:00.000
But every manufacturer has some price that suits it minimally.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:03.000
If the oil is cheaper,

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:07.000
it simply will not be engaged in this price.

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:12.000
And the difference in these minimum prices

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:18.000
is due to the differences in oil production costs at different oil fields.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:22.000
So, we have three oil fields.

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:27.000
The first field is in the Middle East.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:33.000
Let's assume that the minimum price that suits the Arabs

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:38.000
is, let's say, 5 dollars per barrel.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:43.000
This is the minimum price that suits the Arabs.

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:50.000
The second oil field is located in Siberia.

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:53.000
There, the cost of production is higher.

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:59.000
And let's assume that the minimum price that suits the Russian firm

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:03.000
is 10 dollars per barrel.

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:08.000
I repeat, if the price is lower than 10 dollars per barrel,

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:11.000
I believe that the oil production becomes unprofitable

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:13.000
and the Russians stop producing oil.

01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:17.000
And finally, the third oil field is located in Norway,

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:19.000
on the shelf of the North Sea.

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:27.000
The minimum price that suits the Norwegians is, let's say, 15 dollars per barrel.

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:35.000
I want to emphasize once again that at every oil field

01:07:36.000 --> 01:07:40.000
you can only extract one barley per field.

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:43.000
Now let's reason.

01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:49.000
Let's assume that the market price of oil

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:54.000
has fallen by less than 5 dollars per barrel.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:59.000
How much oil will be extracted?

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:03.000
It is obvious that under such conditions, no one will extract oil.

01:08:04.000 --> 01:08:08.000
And the supply of oil to the market will be zero.

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:13.000
And if the price reaches 5 dollars per barrel?

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:21.000
I repeat, 5 dollars per barrel is the minimum price that suits the Arabs.

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:24.000
It suits no one else, only them.

01:08:25.000 --> 01:08:31.000
So, at the price of 5 dollars, how much oil will be supplied to the world market?

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:35.000
Only one barrel.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:41.000
Good. And if the oil prices rise and the price will be 10 dollars per barrel?

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:46.000
We assume that the Arabs simply cannot extract more than one barrel.

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:49.000
But who will be involved?

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:51.000
The Siberians.

01:08:52.000 --> 01:08:54.000
The Russian oil company will start extracting oil.

01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:58.000
10 dollars per barrel is the minimum price that suits it.

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:02.000
So, how much oil will be supplied to the world market?

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:05.000
Already 2 barrels. The Arabs and the Russians.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:08.000
And how much oil will be supplied to the world market?

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:11.000
2 barrels.

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:16.000
Good. And if the price reaches 15 dollars per barrel?

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:19.000
Who will be involved? The Norwegians.

01:09:20.000 --> 01:09:22.000
And they are already extracting oil.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:25.000
They extract their own barrel.

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:31.000
And the supply of oil to the world market reaches 3 barrels.

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:34.000
What have we got?

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:39.000
We can transfer this table to the graph.

01:09:40.000 --> 01:09:42.000
Look.

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:49.000
The x-axis shows the quantity of oil.

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:54.000
The y-axis shows the price of the product.

01:09:55.000 --> 01:10:06.000
So, at the price of 5 dollars per barrel, how much oil is extracted?

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:09.000
They offer 1 barrel to the world market.

