And now, for some reason, they offer to sell at the same price.

01:13:20.000 --> 01:13:21.000
How much?

01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:23.000
Not 2, but 3.

01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:25.000
And what happens?

01:13:26.000 --> 01:13:35.000
The supply curve shifts to the right.

01:13:36.000 --> 01:13:44.000
That is, when the supply increases, the supply curve shifts to the right-down.

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:48.000
And when the supply decreases, what does it mean?

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:58.000
It means that at the same price, they offer less goods than before.

01:13:58.000 --> 01:14:07.000
Let's say, before, at the price of $10 per barrel, they offered to sell 2 barrels of oil.

01:14:08.000 --> 01:14:11.000
And now, for some reason, they offer only 1 barrel.

01:14:12.000 --> 01:14:13.000
And what happens?

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:23.000
The supply curve shifts to the left-up.

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:26.000
Once again.

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:34.000
When the supply increases, the supply curve shifts to the right-down.

01:14:35.000 --> 01:14:40.000
When the supply decreases, the supply curve shifts to the left-up.

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:45.000
Let's see now why this can happen.

