01:56:04.000 --> 01:56:06.000
The  coefficient shows

01:56:07.000 --> 01:56:10.000
how many percent the output can be changed

01:56:11.000 --> 01:56:14.000
when the labor is changed by 1%.

01:56:18.000 --> 01:56:20.000
Knowing the production function,

01:56:21.000 --> 01:56:25.000
we can measure the scale of the output.

01:56:28.000 --> 01:56:31.000
Read the definition on the next slide.

01:56:33.000 --> 01:56:35.000
The scale of the output shows

01:56:36.000 --> 01:56:40.000
how many times the output increases

01:56:41.000 --> 01:56:44.000
when all factors of production,

01:56:45.000 --> 01:56:48.000
that is, all resources, are increased at the same time.

01:56:50.000 --> 01:56:53.000
To produce something,

01:56:54.000 --> 01:56:55.000
we need resources.

01:56:56.000 --> 01:56:58.000
Let's say we use two factors,

01:56:59.000 --> 01:57:01.000
labor and capital.

01:57:02.000 --> 01:57:05.000
Let's assume that we increased

01:57:06.000 --> 01:57:09.000
the amount of labor and capital by 2 times,

01:57:10.000 --> 01:57:13.000
that is, we built a factory twice as large.

01:57:14.000 --> 01:57:17.000
This means that we use twice as much capital,

01:57:17.000 --> 01:57:19.000
we build twice as many machines,

01:57:20.000 --> 01:57:22.000
and we use twice as much labor.

01:57:23.000 --> 01:57:25.000
What will happen to production?

01:57:26.000 --> 01:57:28.000
Production will increase, of course,

01:57:29.000 --> 01:57:31.000
but not by 2 times.

01:57:32.000 --> 01:57:34.000
There are three possible cases.

01:57:35.000 --> 01:57:37.000
In the first case,

01:57:38.000 --> 01:57:41.000
we increase the number of factors by 2 times,

01:57:42.000 --> 01:57:44.000
and the output increases by 3 times.

01:57:45.000 --> 01:57:47.000
In this case, we say

01:57:48.000 --> 01:57:52.000
that there is an increasing scale of output.

01:57:53.000 --> 01:57:55.000
In the second case,

01:57:56.000 --> 01:57:58.000
we increase the output,

01:57:59.000 --> 01:58:01.000
we increase all factors, excuse me,

01:58:02.000 --> 01:58:03.000
by 1 time,

01:58:04.000 --> 01:58:06.000
that is, labor and capital increased by 1 time,

01:58:07.000 --> 01:58:09.000
by 2 times, in my example,

01:58:10.000 --> 01:58:12.000
and the output increases by less than 1 time,

01:58:12.000 --> 01:58:14.000
for example, by 1.5 times.

01:58:15.000 --> 01:58:19.000
Then we say that there is a decreasing scale of output.

01:58:20.000 --> 01:58:22.000
In the third case,

01:58:23.000 --> 01:58:25.000
we increased both factors,

01:58:26.000 --> 01:58:28.000
all factors increased by 1 time,

01:58:29.000 --> 01:58:31.000
in my example, by 2 times,

01:58:32.000 --> 01:58:34.000
and the output increased by 1 time,

01:58:35.000 --> 01:58:37.000
by 2 times, too.

01:58:38.000 --> 01:58:41.000
Then we say that there is a constant scale of output.

01:58:42.000 --> 01:58:44.000
It plays a very important role

01:58:45.000 --> 01:58:48.000
in determining the optimal size of the enterprise.

01:58:49.000 --> 01:58:51.000
Let's say, Zhiguli.

01:58:52.000 --> 01:58:54.000
They can be assembled in a small workshop.

01:58:55.000 --> 01:58:57.000
Of course, they can.

01:58:58.000 --> 01:59:01.000
AvtoVAZ, as a production complex,

01:59:02.000 --> 01:59:04.000
in terms of labor and capital,

01:59:05.000 --> 01:59:07.000
is supposed to be 100 times larger

01:59:08.000 --> 01:59:10.000
than such a small workshop.

01:59:10.000 --> 01:59:14.000
That is, it uses the production factors 100 times more.

01:59:15.000 --> 01:59:17.000
And the output of AvtoVAZ,

01:59:18.000 --> 01:59:21.000
at the same time, increases by 200 or 300 times.

01:59:22.000 --> 01:59:24.000
What does this mean?

01:59:25.000 --> 01:59:27.000
That it is more effective for AvtoVAZ

01:59:28.000 --> 01:59:30.000
to assemble machines at a large factory

01:59:31.000 --> 01:59:33.000
than in a small workshop.

01:59:34.000 --> 01:59:36.000
So, if the return on scale increases,

01:59:36.000 --> 01:59:40.000
we should increase the size of the enterprise.

01:59:45.000 --> 01:59:47.000
Another example.

01:59:48.000 --> 01:59:50.000
In Soviet times,

01:59:51.000 --> 01:59:53.000
people were very fond of building giant enterprises,

01:59:54.000 --> 01:59:56.000
including agriculture.

01:59:57.000 --> 02:00:00.000
For example, they built giant pig farms

02:00:01.000 --> 02:00:04.000
for thousands or even tens of thousands of cattle.

02:00:04.000 --> 02:00:08.000
Not only did the entire ecology fly within a radius of 100 kilometers,

02:00:09.000 --> 02:00:11.000
but what else was there?

02:00:12.000 --> 02:00:14.000
Let's say, a giant pig farm

02:00:15.000 --> 02:00:17.000
uses production factors

02:00:18.000 --> 02:00:20.000
100 times more than a small farm.

02:00:21.000 --> 02:00:23.000
And the production of meat

02:00:24.000 --> 02:00:27.000
is, let's say, 10 times more.

02:00:28.000 --> 02:00:30.000
What does this mean?

02:00:30.000 --> 02:00:32.000
That a large enterprise in agriculture

02:00:33.000 --> 02:00:35.000
is economically inefficient.

02:00:36.000 --> 02:00:40.000
That is why small farms are quite effective in agriculture.

02:00:41.000 --> 02:00:45.000
And when we increase the size of the enterprise,

02:00:46.000 --> 02:00:49.000
we sooner or later come to a situation

02:00:50.000 --> 02:00:53.000
where the increasing return on scale

02:00:54.000 --> 02:00:57.000
is constantly changing, and then decreasing.

02:00:57.000 --> 02:01:02.000
This means that we should not increase the size of the enterprise any further.

02:01:03.000 --> 02:01:07.000
It is better to enjoy a larger number of enterprises, but smaller in size.

02:01:09.000 --> 02:01:12.000
Knowing the production function,

02:01:13.000 --> 02:01:17.000
we can always calculate the costs of the enterprise.

02:01:18.000 --> 02:01:20.000
Here we come to the second question.

02:01:20.000 --> 02:01:25.000
Economists divide costs into accounting and economic.

02:01:26.000 --> 02:01:30.000
The definition of accounting costs, please look at the slide.

02:01:31.000 --> 02:01:34.000
The accounting costs of a company

02:01:35.000 --> 02:01:39.000
are the sum of its actual payments for the purchased resources.

02:01:40.000 --> 02:01:44.000
The sum of the actual payments for the purchased resources.

02:01:44.000 --> 02:01:46.000
This is very easy.

02:01:47.000 --> 02:01:49.000
In order to produce something,

02:01:50.000 --> 02:01:53.000
the company needs a wide variety of resources.

02:01:54.000 --> 02:01:57.000
The company buys these resources.

02:01:58.000 --> 02:02:00.000
And then the accountant

02:02:01.000 --> 02:02:04.000
sums up all these payments for the purchased resources

02:02:05.000 --> 02:02:08.000
and puts them into the account.

02:02:09.000 --> 02:02:11.000
And then the accountant

02:02:11.000 --> 02:02:14.000
sums up all these payments for the purchased resources

02:02:15.000 --> 02:02:17.000
and puts them into the account.

02:02:18.000 --> 02:02:23.000
Let's look at the simplest example.

02:02:24.000 --> 02:02:31.000
Let's look at the simplest example of accounting costs.

02:02:32.000 --> 02:02:36.000
Suppose the company uses equipment

02:02:36.000 --> 02:02:43.000
worth 200 rubles and service life, let's say, 5 years.

02:02:44.000 --> 02:02:47.000
Obviously, the whole cost of equipment

02:02:48.000 --> 02:02:50.000
cannot be attributed to the expense of one year.

02:02:51.000 --> 02:02:53.000
Amortization must be used.

02:02:54.000 --> 02:02:57.000
When using the simplest linear amortization,

02:02:58.000 --> 02:03:01.000
the expenses of one year will be attributed, respectively,

02:03:02.000 --> 02:03:05.000
200 divided by 5, 40 rubles.

02:03:06.000 --> 02:03:08.000
That is, the accountant makes his report.

02:03:09.000 --> 02:03:12.000
Amortization is 40 rubles.

02:03:14.000 --> 02:03:15.000
Next.

02:03:16.000 --> 02:03:19.000
Suppose the company uses raw materials and materials

02:03:20.000 --> 02:03:24.000
worth 80 rubles annually.

02:03:25.000 --> 02:03:29.000
The accountant writes, raw materials 80.

02:03:29.000 --> 02:03:37.000
And the company pays, let's assume, 60 rubles per year in salary.

02:03:38.000 --> 02:03:44.000
The accountant writes, salary 60.

02:03:45.000 --> 02:03:50.000
Now let's assume that the equipment was bought on credit

02:03:51.000 --> 02:03:54.000
at 10% annual.

02:03:54.000 --> 02:04:00.000
10% of 200 equipment costs are 20 rubles.

02:04:01.000 --> 02:04:07.000
So, the percentage on credit annually will be 20 rubles.

02:04:08.000 --> 02:04:11.000
The percentage on credit is another 20 rubles.

02:04:12.000 --> 02:04:18.000
Let's assume that the company does not make any more payments.

02:04:19.000 --> 02:04:22.000
But it does not make any administrative, transport expenses,

02:04:23.000 --> 02:04:27.000
advertising, research, does not pay taxes related to cost.

02:04:28.000 --> 02:04:30.000
None of this.

02:04:31.000 --> 02:04:35.000
The accountant sums up all these payments and writes,

02:04:36.000 --> 02:04:41.000
the sum of accounting expenses is 200 rubles.

02:04:42.000 --> 02:04:48.000
The economist has a slightly different view.

02:04:52.000 --> 02:04:59.000
Economic expenses are alternative expenses.

02:05:00.000 --> 02:05:04.000
They represent the value of those benefits

02:05:04.000 --> 02:05:10.000
that could be obtained with the most profitable

02:05:11.000 --> 02:05:16.000
of all alternative ways of using limited resources.

02:05:18.000 --> 02:05:21.000
I'm afraid it's not very clear, but it can be simpler.

02:05:22.000 --> 02:05:29.000
In practical calculations, economic expenses include,

02:05:29.000 --> 02:05:34.000
in addition to the obvious or accounting expenses,

02:05:35.000 --> 02:05:38.000
also the unclear expenses.

02:05:39.000 --> 02:05:44.000
We can write that economic expenses are equal to

02:05:45.000 --> 02:05:51.000
accounting expenses plus some other unclear expenses.

02:05:52.000 --> 02:05:56.000
What are accounting expenses?

02:05:57.000 --> 02:05:59.000
I've already said.

02:06:00.000 --> 02:06:03.000
It is not clear what are the unclear expenses.

02:06:04.000 --> 02:06:06.000
Let's read.

02:06:07.000 --> 02:06:13.000
The unclear expenses are the amount of unpaid income

02:06:14.000 --> 02:06:18.000
of the company on its own resources.

02:06:19.000 --> 02:06:24.000
We are talking about the income that the company management

02:06:24.000 --> 02:06:30.000
could get using its resources,

02:06:31.000 --> 02:06:35.000
not in this business, but in some other way.

02:06:38.000 --> 02:06:41.000
Let's analyze this.

02:06:42.000 --> 02:06:47.000
Imagine that you founded your own business.

02:06:48.000 --> 02:06:52.000
Obviously, you came to this business with a lot of money.

02:06:52.000 --> 02:06:55.000
What did you bring with you?

02:06:58.000 --> 02:07:03.000
Perhaps, some amount of money capital.

02:07:04.000 --> 02:07:06.000
Let's say, 100 rubles.

02:07:07.000 --> 02:07:12.000
Could you use this capital alternatively?

02:07:14.000 --> 02:07:16.000
Of course, you could.

02:07:17.000 --> 02:07:21.000
What is the simplest alternative to use this money?

02:07:22.000 --> 02:07:25.000
You could put it in the bank.

02:07:26.000 --> 02:07:29.000
Then you would get a percentage.

02:07:30.000 --> 02:07:33.000
If you invested this money in your own company,

02:07:34.000 --> 02:07:37.000
you would lose this percentage.

02:07:39.000 --> 02:07:43.000
And this unpaid percentage

02:07:44.000 --> 02:07:49.000
would be included in the unclear expenses of the company.

02:07:50.000 --> 02:07:55.000
Let's say, you invested 100 rubles in your business.

02:07:56.000 --> 02:08:00.000
You had to close your bank account.

02:08:01.000 --> 02:08:07.000
Therefore, you lost 10% of the invested money.

02:08:08.000 --> 02:08:12.000
I suppose that the bank pays 10% of the investment.

02:08:12.000 --> 02:08:18.000
So, what is included in the unclear expenses?

02:08:19.000 --> 02:08:24.000
The unpaid percentage

02:08:25.000 --> 02:08:29.000
of the investment in your own business.

02:08:30.000 --> 02:08:33.000
You got this money for free.

02:08:34.000 --> 02:08:37.000
But it doesn't mean that you shouldn't use it.

02:08:37.000 --> 02:08:40.000
You invested 100 rubles,

02:08:41.000 --> 02:08:44.000
lost 10% of the money

02:08:45.000 --> 02:08:48.000
that you could have got if you kept this money in the bank.

02:08:49.000 --> 02:08:52.000
And, accordingly, this unpaid percentage

02:08:53.000 --> 02:08:56.000
of 10 rubles would be included in the unclear expenses.

02:08:57.000 --> 02:09:00.000
Then, in order to start your own business,

02:09:01.000 --> 02:09:04.000
you had to quit your job.

02:09:04.000 --> 02:09:07.000
And you probably worked for a hire.

02:09:08.000 --> 02:09:09.000
So, what did you lose?

02:09:10.000 --> 02:09:11.000
The salary.

02:09:12.000 --> 02:09:14.000
The unpaid salary

02:09:15.000 --> 02:09:18.000
would also be included in the unclear expenses of the company.

02:09:19.000 --> 02:09:23.000
Let's say, you earned 200 rubles by working for a hire.

02:09:24.000 --> 02:09:26.000
You founded your own business,

02:09:27.000 --> 02:09:29.000
and you lost this 200 rubles.

02:09:29.000 --> 02:09:32.000
The economists include this 200 rubles of unpaid salary

02:09:33.000 --> 02:09:35.000
in the unclear expenses of your company.

02:09:36.000 --> 02:09:37.000
I write down

02:09:38.000 --> 02:09:44.000
the unpaid salary.

02:09:45.000 --> 02:09:48.000
Let's say, how much was there? 20 rubles.

02:09:49.000 --> 02:09:50.000
The unpaid salary.

02:09:51.000 --> 02:09:53.000
Another assumption.

02:09:54.000 --> 02:09:56.000
Let's suppose that for the sake of your business

02:09:56.000 --> 02:09:59.000
you turned your apartment into an office or a warehouse.

02:10:01.000 --> 02:10:03.000
What did you lose in this case?

02:10:04.000 --> 02:10:05.000
How to estimate your losses?

02:10:06.000 --> 02:10:10.000
You could have rented this apartment.

02:10:11.000 --> 02:10:14.000
By renting it, you could have received,

02:10:15.000 --> 02:10:16.000
let's say,

02:10:17.000 --> 02:10:19.000
another 20 rubles per year.

02:10:21.000 --> 02:10:24.000
By giving this apartment to your business,

02:10:24.000 --> 02:10:27.000
you lost this 20 rubles.

02:10:28.000 --> 02:10:30.000
So, the unpaid salary

02:10:31.000 --> 02:10:34.000
would also be included in the unclear expenses.

02:10:40.000 --> 02:10:43.000
The unpaid salary is 20 rubles.

02:10:44.000 --> 02:10:45.000
Well, that's good.

02:10:46.000 --> 02:10:49.000
Summing up all these lost income,

02:10:50.000 --> 02:10:51.000
we get

02:10:51.000 --> 02:10:56.000
the unpaid expenses of the company.

02:10:58.000 --> 02:10:59.000
They are

02:11:02.000 --> 02:11:03.000
50 rubles.

02:11:04.000 --> 02:11:05.000
It turns out

02:11:06.000 --> 02:11:09.000
that the total economic expenses of the company

02:11:10.000 --> 02:11:13.000
are 200 rubles of accounting expenses,

02:11:14.000 --> 02:11:16.000
50 rubles of unpaid expenses,

02:11:17.000 --> 02:11:19.000
and 250 rubles in total.

02:11:21.000 --> 02:11:24.000
But now we need to answer the most important question.

02:11:25.000 --> 02:11:27.000
Why do economists make up the original?

02:11:28.000 --> 02:11:30.000
What did they come up with

02:11:31.000 --> 02:11:34.000
in addition to the obvious or accounting expenses,

02:11:35.000 --> 02:11:36.000
which are obvious to everyone,

02:11:37.000 --> 02:11:38.000
some other unclear expenses,

02:11:39.000 --> 02:11:40.000
which, I repeat,

02:11:41.000 --> 02:11:43.000
the company does not even pay to anyone?

02:11:45.000 --> 02:11:49.000
The unclear expenses are the income

02:11:49.000 --> 02:11:53.000
that entrepreneurs lost

02:11:55.000 --> 02:11:58.000
by investing their resources in the company,

02:11:59.000 --> 02:12:00.000
which they provided to the company,

02:12:01.000 --> 02:12:02.000
supposedly for free.

02:12:03.000 --> 02:12:04.000
But why?

02:12:05.000 --> 02:12:07.000
Without knowing the unclear expenses,

02:12:08.000 --> 02:12:09.000
we cannot assess

02:12:10.000 --> 02:12:14.000
how profitable this business is to entrepreneurs.

02:12:16.000 --> 02:12:18.000
So, I have already said about the expenses.

