02:23:59.000 --> 02:24:02.000
Let's start the third question of the topic.

02:24:03.000 --> 02:24:05.000
The types of expenses.

02:24:06.000 --> 02:24:11.000
All expenses, both accounting and economic,

02:24:12.000 --> 02:24:17.000
can be divided into constant and variable.

02:24:18.000 --> 02:24:21.000
What is the basis of such a division?

02:24:22.000 --> 02:24:27.000
Look, let's say the company increases the production.

02:24:28.000 --> 02:24:32.000
And it is clear that with the increase of production,

02:24:33.000 --> 02:24:37.000
some expenses change,

02:24:38.000 --> 02:24:40.000
and others remain unchanged.

02:24:41.000 --> 02:24:45.000
Those expenses that do not change with the increase of production,

02:24:46.000 --> 02:24:49.000
we call constant expenses.

02:24:50.000 --> 02:24:54.000
And those expenses that change with the increase of production,

02:24:54.000 --> 02:24:58.000
we call variable expenses.

02:24:59.000 --> 02:25:04.000
Why are expenses generally divided into constant and variable?

02:25:05.000 --> 02:25:11.000
Because we also divide the production factors into constant and variable.

02:25:12.000 --> 02:25:16.000
The fact is that some production factors

02:25:17.000 --> 02:25:20.000
can be easily and quickly changed

02:25:21.000 --> 02:25:24.000
with the increase of production.

02:25:25.000 --> 02:25:30.000
Let's say, it is easy enough for a company to hire new workers.

02:25:31.000 --> 02:25:34.000
Workers are a variable factor of production.

02:25:35.000 --> 02:25:38.000
But a company needs a certain amount of time

02:25:39.000 --> 02:25:41.000
to acquire new equipment,

02:25:42.000 --> 02:25:44.000
that is, to use additional capital.

02:25:45.000 --> 02:25:48.000
Therefore, we usually take equipment

02:25:48.000 --> 02:25:53.000
in the short term to the constant factor of production.

02:25:54.000 --> 02:25:58.000
Look at the definition again on the slide.

02:25:59.000 --> 02:26:02.000
Constant expenses are the expenses,

02:26:03.000 --> 02:26:07.000
the amount of which does not change with the change of production.

02:26:08.000 --> 02:26:12.000
That is, these are the expenses of the constant factors of production.

02:26:13.000 --> 02:26:17.000
Amortization, rental fee, interest on credit,

02:26:18.000 --> 02:26:22.000
salary of management are usually related to constant expenses.

02:26:23.000 --> 02:26:27.000
Unclear expenses are also usually related to constant.

02:26:28.000 --> 02:26:30.000
Now variable expenses again.

02:26:31.000 --> 02:26:33.000
Variable expenses are the expenses,

02:26:34.000 --> 02:26:37.000
the amount of which changes with the change of production.

02:26:38.000 --> 02:26:41.000
That is, these are the expenses of the variable factors of production.

02:26:42.000 --> 02:26:45.000
Usually, they include salary of production workers,

02:26:46.000 --> 02:26:48.000
raw materials expenses,

02:26:49.000 --> 02:26:52.000
electricity for technological purposes, and others.

02:26:55.000 --> 02:27:01.000
So, constant expenses and variable expenses.

02:27:03.000 --> 02:27:06.000
If we sum them up,

02:27:07.000 --> 02:27:10.000
we get the total expenses.

02:27:10.000 --> 02:27:12.000
Look at the slide.

02:27:13.000 --> 02:27:16.000
Fc is the fixed cost.

02:27:17.000 --> 02:27:21.000
Vc is the variable cost.

02:27:22.000 --> 02:27:25.000
The total cost is TC.

02:27:26.000 --> 02:27:28.000
The total expenses of the company.

02:27:31.000 --> 02:27:36.000
It is also very important to know the expenses per unit of production,

02:27:37.000 --> 02:27:39.000
or the average expenses.

02:27:40.000 --> 02:27:42.000
Average constant expenses.

02:27:43.000 --> 02:27:45.000
We denote them by the letter AFC.

02:27:46.000 --> 02:27:47.000
Look at the slide.

02:27:48.000 --> 02:27:52.000
These are the constant expenses per unit of production.

02:27:53.000 --> 02:27:56.000
So it turns out that AFC is equal to

02:27:57.000 --> 02:28:00.000
FC is the constant expenses divided by the volume of production Q.

02:28:02.000 --> 02:28:06.000
Average variable expenses AVC.

02:28:06.000 --> 02:28:10.000
These are the variable expenses per unit of production.

02:28:11.000 --> 02:28:13.000
How to calculate them?

02:28:14.000 --> 02:28:17.000
We divide the total amount of variable expenses by the volume of production.

02:28:18.000 --> 02:28:19.000
Look at the formula.

02:28:21.000 --> 02:28:25.000
And finally, the average total expenses.

02:28:26.000 --> 02:28:31.000
These are the total expenses per unit of production.

02:28:32.000 --> 02:28:34.000
How to calculate?

02:28:34.000 --> 02:28:37.000
We can divide the total expenses, the total cost, TC,

02:28:38.000 --> 02:28:40.000
by the volume of production Q.

02:28:41.000 --> 02:28:43.000
Or we can calculate it in another way.

02:28:44.000 --> 02:28:48.000
We can sum up the average constant and average variable expenses.

02:28:53.000 --> 02:29:01.000
The marginal cost is a very important role in economic analysis.

02:29:02.000 --> 02:29:07.000
The marginal costs are the addition of the total costs

02:29:08.000 --> 02:29:11.000
when the volume of production is one unit.

02:29:12.000 --> 02:29:13.000
Look at the formula.

02:29:14.000 --> 02:29:19.000
MC is equal to delta TC divided by delta Q.

02:29:21.000 --> 02:29:22.000
How to understand it?

02:29:23.000 --> 02:29:28.000
Let's say you have already produced a certain number of units of production.

02:29:29.000 --> 02:29:37.000
You want to produce one more additional unit of production.

02:29:43.000 --> 02:29:46.000
To produce an additional unit of production,

02:29:47.000 --> 02:29:50.000
you need to bear additional costs.

02:29:51.000 --> 02:29:59.000
These additional costs required by the production of an additional unit of production

02:30:00.000 --> 02:30:02.000
are the marginal costs.

02:30:04.000 --> 02:30:07.000
But look, when do we increase the volume of production?

02:30:09.000 --> 02:30:11.000
And when do we increase the total costs?

02:30:12.000 --> 02:30:18.000
After all, the total costs are made up of constant and variable costs.

02:30:19.000 --> 02:30:21.000
But only variable costs are increased.

02:30:22.000 --> 02:30:28.000
Constant costs do not change in a short period of time.

02:30:30.000 --> 02:30:39.000
So, the addition of the total costs is equal to the addition of the variable costs.

02:30:39.000 --> 02:30:46.000
So, the marginal costs can be calculated by dividing delta VC,

02:30:47.000 --> 02:30:51.000
the increase of the variable costs, by the delta of the production.

02:30:54.000 --> 02:31:01.000
To better understand this, I will give an elementary example of calculation of costs.

02:31:02.000 --> 02:31:04.000
Please look at the slide.

02:31:05.000 --> 02:31:09.000
We have two volumes of production here, 10 and 11.

02:31:10.000 --> 02:31:12.000
What are the constant costs?

02:31:13.000 --> 02:31:15.000
All the time 50.

02:31:16.000 --> 02:31:18.000
They do not change with the change in production,

02:31:19.000 --> 02:31:21.000
by determining the constant costs.

02:31:22.000 --> 02:31:23.000
And what are the changes?

02:31:24.000 --> 02:31:25.000
The variables change.

02:31:26.000 --> 02:31:29.000
Suppose at the time of production 10 they were equal to 100 rubles,

02:31:30.000 --> 02:31:33.000
and at the time of production 11 they were 105 rubles.

02:31:34.000 --> 02:31:37.000
All other parameters are easy to calculate.

02:31:39.000 --> 02:31:41.000
What are the total costs equal to?

02:31:42.000 --> 02:31:45.000
How much were they before, at the time of production 10?

02:31:46.000 --> 02:31:48.000
50 plus 100, that is, 150.

02:31:49.000 --> 02:31:51.000
Now they are at the time of production 11.

02:31:52.000 --> 02:31:54.000
50 plus 105, 155.

02:31:55.000 --> 02:31:57.000
How to calculate the average constant?

02:31:58.000 --> 02:32:02.000
It is very easy. We divide the constant costs by the volume of the production.

02:32:02.000 --> 02:32:05.000
50 divided by 10 is 5.

02:32:06.000 --> 02:32:11.000
5 rubles of constant costs per unit of production at the time of production 10.

02:32:12.000 --> 02:32:14.000
And at the time of production 11, how do we calculate?

02:32:15.000 --> 02:32:19.000
50 divided by 11 is approximately 4.55.

02:32:20.000 --> 02:32:24.000
These are the average constant costs at the new volume of production.